<div id="review_1940684269" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1940684269" />
    <a title="Rachel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/37210914-rachel"><img alt="Rachel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1416673905p2/37210914.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1940684269?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rachel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rachel" href="/user/show/37210914-rachel">Rachel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37210914-rachel?shelf=bi-visibility">bi-visibility</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37210914-rachel?shelf=m-m-fantasy-scifi-pnr-romance">m-m-fantasy-scifi-pnr-romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37210914-rachel?shelf=ya-and-na-romance">ya-and-na-romance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1940684269" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6495540645938305644">This is a sweet YA romance with charming characters. I wanted to love this story, and for the most part, I did enjoy it a lot, but... <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[Nate comes from a family with the ability to see and communicate with ghosts. Despite that fact that his grandmother employs these skills, Nate&apos;s mother reacts terribly when Nate demonstrates the same skills. His mother refuses to speak with him, and kicks Nate out of the house. I know it is ironic that I find it completely believable that Nate is a</span></span>
  <span id="freeText6495540645938305644" style="display:none">This is a sweet YA romance with charming characters. I wanted to love this story, and for the most part, I did enjoy it a lot, but... <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Nate comes from a family with the ability to see and communicate with ghosts. Despite that fact that his grandmother employs these skills, Nate's mother reacts terribly when Nate demonstrates the same skills. His mother refuses to speak with him, and kicks Nate out of the house. I know it is ironic that I find it completely believable that Nate is able to speak with spirits, but find it utterly implausible that his mother would throw him out because of this gift. There is a point in the story where Nate and his mother begin to reconcile, and that read contrived and false to me. It is important for authors to realize that HEA/HFN endings don’t have to always include family reconciliation. Also, despite being charmed by Nate and his internal voice, I was saddened to see him demonstrate such low self-esteem. He never seemed to believe that he was worthy of anything good in life, and I despaired to see his defeatist attitude. James is sweet, but he also behaves erratically. Despite admitting that he is bisexual, he seems strangely reluctant to admit that he has romantic feelings for Nate. It also boggled my mind that James would be so blind to the fact that Nate was devastated when James started dating a female classmate.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> Complaints aside, the story is lovely and enjoyable, and I’m glad that I read it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6495540645938305644" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


