<span id="freeTextContainer13165495178990747977">4.5 stars. &lt;333333 <br/><br/>A Boy Worth Knowing is one of the best YA books I’ve read recently. Wonderfully realistic, witty, and charming, and I so, so, so adored Nate. I loved James, too…but Nate, you guys…he was fantastic. Jennifer Cosgrove gave him such an authentic voice, I truly felt like I was inside a high school boy’s head. The same was true for James as well; in fact, all the characters read as very true to life. There’s nothing that bothers me more in reading YA than it feeling forced, or pain</span>
  <span id="freeText13165495178990747977" style="display:none">4.5 stars. &lt;333333 <br /><br />A Boy Worth Knowing is one of the best YA books I’ve read recently. Wonderfully realistic, witty, and charming, and I so, so, so adored Nate. I loved James, too…but Nate, you guys…he was fantastic. Jennifer Cosgrove gave him such an authentic voice, I truly felt like I was inside a high school boy’s head. The same was true for James as well; in fact, all the characters read as very true to life. There’s nothing that bothers me more in reading YA than it feeling forced, or painfully obvious that it’s anything but a teenager or young adult writing the story. Cosgrove definitely seems to have the knack for it, though.<br /><br />See my full review here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.thenovelapproachreviews.com/review-a-boy-worth-knowing-by-jennifer-cosgrove/">http://www.thenovelapproachreviews.co...</a></span>
