<div id="review_1928390194" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1928390194" />
    <a title="Tess" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32894729-tess"><img alt="Tess" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1424452966p2/32894729.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1928390194?book_show_action=true">Mar 23, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tess" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tess" href="/user/show/32894729-tess">Tess</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32894729-tess?shelf=ya-mm">ya-mm</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32894729-tess?shelf=paranormal">paranormal</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1928390194" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9932309268548700942"><b>4 stars</b><br/><br/>I&apos;m a big sucker for YA m/m romance that has a coming of age feel, so I was very excited to read this. And in the end I liked it, but not as much as I wanted to. What I liked most was Nate - I loved his voice and I really understood and felt for him. What I didn&apos;t like? First, even though we don&apos;t really see the mom much, I thought that part was a little over the top. <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[I guess as a mom I can&apos;t really see Nate&apos;s mom actually kicking him out of the house and refusing to be in </span></span>
  <span id="freeText9932309268548700942" style="display:none"><b>4 stars</b><br /><br />I'm a big sucker for YA m/m romance that has a coming of age feel, so I was very excited to read this. And in the end I liked it, but not as much as I wanted to. What I liked most was Nate - I loved his voice and I really understood and felt for him. What I didn't like? First, even though we don't really see the mom much, I thought that part was a little over the top. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I guess as a mom I can't really see Nate's mom actually kicking him out of the house and refusing to be in touch with him just because of his ability to talk to ghosts <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. Second, there were some things about the development of the relationship with James that weren't believable to me. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[We find out at the end that James was attracted to Nate at the beginning and wanted to kiss him the first time they went to a movie. After that movie they became very close friends. Then Nate tells James that he's gay. Even though James is bisexual and apparently not closeted (he'd had a boyfriend before), he doesn't tell Nate at this time?? It doesn't seem believable. Then out of nowhere James starts to date that girl. Really? Then he can't understand why Nate is all upset? I don't know, it just seemed a little, perhaps, contrived just to add drama. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> I'm probably just being too picky! </span>
